      "writtenOn": "2016-07-26T09:30:47Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The change doesn\u0027t actually change the behavior at all:\npreviously the parameter type was T*, so function used to return a ScopedPtr\u003cT, ...\u003e - which is the same as std::remove_pointer\u003cT*\u003e::type\nNow the only difference is that T includes the star in it, so for conventional usages we can assume T \u003d\u003d U*, and return value is ScopedPtr\u003cU, ...\u003e \u003d\u003d ScopedPtr\u003cstd::remove_pointer\u003cT\u003e::type, ...\u003e\n\nThe real difference here\u0027s in nullptr_t treatment. Old code needed a pointer here, so makeCustomScopedPtr(nullptr) just didn\u0027t compile. Now it does, as remove_pointer\u003cNonPointer\u003e returns the type itself",
      "parentUuid": "0a617bbb_112afce4",
